---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeTabs from '../../components/CodeTabs.astro';

const codeInstall = `npm install @fundamental-engine/vanilla`;

const codeCanvas = `<canvas id="field"></canvas>

<style>
  #field { position: fixed; inset: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; pointer-events: none; }
</style>`;

const codeField = `import { createField, browserHost } from '@fundamental-engine/vanilla';

const canvas = document.getElementById('field');

const field = createField(canvas, {
  host: browserHost(document.body),
  render: 'dots',   // draw particles — the default is 'none' (signals only)
  density: 0.8,
});`;

const codeBody = `<h1 data-body="attract" data-strength="0.8" data-range="280">
  Hello world
</h1>`;

const codeSignalsHtml = `<!-- Add data-feedback to receive live CSS vars -->
<div data-body="attract" data-feedback id="hero">Watch me</div>`;

const codeSignalsCss = `/* Use them in CSS — no JavaScript polling needed */
#hero {
  opacity: calc(0.4 + var(--field-density, 0) * 0.6);
  scale: calc(1 + var(--field-attention, 0) * 0.08);
}`;
---
<DocsLayout
  title="Getting started — 5 minutes to your first field"
  description="Install Fundamental, create a field, see particles move, and read the signals. No framework required."
>
  <h1>Getting started</h1>
  <p>
    Five minutes: install → canvas → field → particles → read the signals.
    No framework, no build step beyond what you already have.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Install</h2>
  <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'Terminal', lang: 'bash', code: codeInstall }]} />

  <h2>2. Add a canvas to your HTML</h2>
  <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'HTML', lang: 'html', code: codeCanvas }]} />

  <h2>3. Start the field</h2>
  <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'TypeScript', lang: 'ts', code: codeField }]} />
  <p>
    That's it. Particles begin flowing immediately. Any element with
    <code>data-body="attract"</code> pulls matter toward it; the page's content becomes
    part of the field.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Make an element a body</h2>
  <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'HTML', lang: 'html', code: codeBody }]} />
  <p>
    Bodies bend the field. <code>attract</code> gathers matter; <code>repel</code> pushes
    it away. Strength (0–1) scales the pull; range (px) sets how far it reaches.
    See the <a href="/docs/api/attributes">data-* attribute reference</a> for all tokens.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Read the signals (no drawing required)</h2>
  <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'HTML', lang: 'html', code: codeSignalsHtml }]} />
  <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'CSS', lang: 'css', code: codeSignalsCss }]} />
  <p>
    The field writes <code>--field-density</code>, <code>--field-attention</code>, and
    <code>--field-temperature</code> directly onto elements with <code>data-feedback</code>.
    CSS reads them — zero JS event listeners required for basic reactivity.
  </p>

  <h2>Next steps</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/docs/tutorial">Full step-by-step tutorial</a> — all three authoring surfaces (web component, React, vanilla)</li>
    <li><a href="/docs/api/options">FieldOptions reference</a> — density, formation, render modes, overlays, and more</li>
    <li><a href="/docs/api/handle">FieldHandle reference</a> — <code>addBody</code>, <code>readParticles</code>, <code>addEdge</code>, <code>sampleScalar</code></li>
    <li><a href="/docs/concepts">Concepts</a> — bodies, reciprocity, and why the field is a substrate</li>
    <li><a href="/lab">Interactive FieldLab</a> — try every force live without writing any code</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
